post_cb({"32871058": {"ParentId": "32868769", "PostTypeId": "2", "CommentCount": "0", "Body": "<p>If only 4 byte multi-character literats are supported, you could use:</p>\n<pre><code>uint64_t x = (((uint64_t)'abcd') &lt;&lt; 32) + 'efgh';\n</code></pre>\n<p>but it would probably end up as 2 literals.</p>\n", "OwnerUserId": "3282056", "LastEditorUserId": "3282056", "LastEditDate": "2015-09-30T16:33:36.533", "Id": "32871058", "Score": "0", "CreationDate": "2015-09-30T16:18:55.843", "LastActivityDate": "2015-09-30T16:33:36.533"}, "32868769": {"CommentCount": "3", "ViewCount": "94", "CreationDate": "2015-09-30T14:30:35.670", "LastActivityDate": "2015-09-30T16:33:36.533", "Title": "Does C++ allow 8 byte long multi-character literals?", "AcceptedAnswerId": "32868947", "PostTypeId": "1", "Id": "32868769", "Score": "3", "Body": "<p>Why is this allowed:</p>\n<p><code>uint32_t x = 'name';</code></p>\n<p>But this gets truncated to 32 bits:</p>\n<p><code>uint64_t x = 'namename';</code></p>\n<p>Is there a way to have an 8-byte long multicharacter literal?</p>\n", "Tags": "<c++>", "OwnerUserId": "2580984", "AnswerCount": "2"}, "bq_ids": {"n4140": {"so_32868769_32868947_0": {"section_id": 5343, "quality": 0.9259259259259259, "length": 25}}, "n3337": {"so_32868769_32868947_0": {"section_id": 5140, "quality": 0.5925925925925926, "length": 16}}, "n4659": {"so_32868769_32868947_0": {"section_id": 6765, "quality": 0.9259259259259259, "length": 25}}}, "32868947": {"ParentId": "32868769", "CommentCount": "4", "Body": "<p>Yes, as long as your compiler has 8-byte <code>int</code>s and supports it.</p>\n<p>The C++ standard is farily terse regarding multi-character literals. This is all it has to say on the matter (C++14, 2.14.3/1):</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_32868769_32868947_0\">An\n  ordinary character literal that contains more than one <em>c-char</em> is a <em>multicharacter literal.</em> A multicharacter\n  literal, or an ordinary character literal containing a single <em>c-char</em> not representable in the execution character\n  set, is conditionally-supported, <strong>has type <code>int</code></strong>, and has an implementation-defined value.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>(Emphasis mine)</p>\n<p>As you see, pretty much all the standard says is that if multicharacter literals are supported (they don't have to be), they are of type <code>int</code>. The value is up to the compiler.</p>\n", "OwnerUserId": "1782465", "PostTypeId": "2", "Id": "32868947", "Score": "7", "CreationDate": "2015-09-30T14:37:57.797", "LastActivityDate": "2015-09-30T14:37:57.797"}});